1533 // combining approach to prove trunc is not required. This can be further
1534 // extended with other instruction combining checks, but for now we handle the
1535 // following case (sub can be "add" and "mul", "nsw + sext" can be "nus + zext")
1536 //
1537 // Src:
1538 //   %c = sub nsw %b, %indvar
1539 //   %d = sext %c to i64
1540 // Dst:
1541 //   %indvar.ext1 = sext %indvar to i64
1542 //   %m = sext %b to i64
1543 //   %d = sub nsw i64 %m, %indvar.ext1
1544 // Therefore, as long as the result of add/sub/mul is extended to wide type, no
1545 // trunc is required regardless of how %b is generated. This pattern is common
1546 // when calculating address in 64 bit architecture
